title: Top 25 shake-up: Gators up, 'Dawgs down, Buckeyes still 1
text:
Story Created: Oct 4, 2015 at 3:55 PM CDT 
By RALPH D. RUSSO AP College Football Writer Ohio State remained No. 1 in The Associated Press college football Top 25 and tied a poll record on Sunday, despite lagging support from the voters. Meanwhile, No. 2 TCU and No. 3 Baylor edged forward, No. 4 Michigan State slipped and No. 5 Utah and No. 6 Clemson took big jumps. After four top-10 teams lost on Saturday, the rankings were rattled and five teams received first-place votes. The Buckeyes received 38 first-place votes, their fewest this season after beginning as the first unanimous preseason No. 1. TCU has five first-place votes, Baylor received 10, Utah has seven and No. 9 Texas A&M has one. Ohio State was the only team in the top 16 to have the same ranking this week as last. The Buckeyes held off Indiana 34-27 on Saturday and have now been top-ranked 101 times, matching Oklahoma for the most in the 79-year history of the media poll. ___ www.collegefootball.ap.org (Copyright 2015 The Associated Press.
